## Autowiring in Spring

---

### 🧠 Concept First

In XML config, you manually wrote:
```xml
<property name="address" ref="addr"/>
```

**Autowiring** lets Spring **automatically figure out** which bean to inject — you don't need to write `ref` manually. Spring matches beans by **name** or **type**.

---

### 📌 Autowiring Modes

| Mode | How Spring matches | XML attribute |
|---|---|---|
| `no` | No autowiring (default) | — |
| `byName` | Matches bean `id` with field name | `autowire="byName"` |
| `byType` | Matches bean `class` type | `autowire="byType"` |
| `constructor` | Like byType but via constructor | `autowire="constructor"` |

---

### 📦 Example Scenario

`Student` depends on `Address` — classic object dependency.

---

#### 📄 Address.java
```java
package com.example;

public class Address {

    private String city;
    private String state;

    public void setCity(String city) {
        this.city = city;
    }

    public void setState(String state) {
        this.state = state;
    }

    public String getCity() { return city; }
    public String getState() { return state; }

    public void show() {
        System.out.println("City: " + city + ", State: " + state);
    }
}
```

---

#### 📄 Student.java
```java
package com.example;

public class Student {

    private String name;
    private Address address;  // object dependency

    public void setName(String name) {
        this.name = name;
    }

    // Setter for dependency — Spring calls this during autowiring
    public void setAddress(Address address) {
        this.address = address;
    }

    public void show() {
        System.out.println("Name: " + name);
        address.show();
    }
}
```

---

### ✅ Mode 1 — `byName`

Spring looks for a bean whose **id matches the field name** (`address`).

```xml
<beans ...>

    <!-- Address bean — id must match field name in Student -->
    <bean id="address" class="com.example.Address">
        <property name="city"  value="Sathyamangalam"/>
        <property name="state" value="Tamil Nadu"/>
    </bean>

    <!-- Student bean — Spring auto-injects 'address' bean by name -->
    <bean id="student"
          class="com.example.Student"
          autowire="byName">
        <property name="name" value="Nivas"/>
        <!-- No need to write: <property name="address" ref="address"/> -->
    </bean>

</beans>
```

> Spring sees field `address` in Student → searches for bean with `id="address"` → injects it ✅

---

### ✅ Mode 2 — `byType`

Spring looks for a bean whose **class type matches** the field type (`Address`).

```xml
<beans ...>

    <!-- id name doesn't matter here, class type matters -->
    <bean id="addr123" class="com.example.Address">
        <property name="city"  value="Coimbatore"/>
        <property name="state" value="Tamil Nadu"/>
    </bean>

    <bean id="student"
          class="com.example.Student"
          autowire="byType">
        <property name="name" value="Nivas"/>
    </bean>

</beans>
```

> Spring sees field type `Address` → searches for bean of type `com.example.Address` → injects it ✅

⚠️ **Problem with byType:** If you have **two beans of the same type**, Spring throws `NoUniqueBeanDefinitionException`.

```xml
<!-- This will CRASH with byType -->
<bean id="addr1" class="com.example.Address"/>
<bean id="addr2" class="com.example.Address"/>
```

---

### ✅ Mode 3 — `constructor`

Like `byType` but Spring uses the **constructor** instead of setter.

```java
// Student.java — needs a constructor
public Student(Address address) {
    this.address = address;
}
```

```xml
<bean id="student"
      class="com.example.Student"
      autowire="constructor">
    <property name="name" value="Nivas"/>
</bean>
```

---

#### 📄 App.java
```java
package com.example;

import org.springframework.context.ApplicationContext;
import org.springframework.context.support.ClassPathXmlApplicationContext;

public class App {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        ApplicationContext ctx =
            new ClassPathXmlApplicationContext("beans.xml");

        Student s = (Student) ctx.getBean("student");
        s.show();
    }
}
```

#### 🖥️ Output
```
Name: Nivas
City: Sathyamangalam, State: Tamil Nadu
```

