### 📌 @Autowired — Annotation Based (Modern Way)

XML autowiring is old. In Spring Boot you use `@Autowired` annotation directly in the class — **no XML needed**.

```java
@Component
public class Student {

    private String name;

    @Autowired          // Spring injects Address bean automatically
    private Address address;

    // No setter needed for field injection!
}
```

#### 3 places you can put `@Autowired`:

```java
// 1. Field Injection (most common, least recommended)
@Autowired
private Address address;

// 2. Setter Injection
@Autowired
public void setAddress(Address address) {
    this.address = address;
}

// 3. Constructor Injection (most recommended)
@Autowired
public Student(Address address) {
    this.address = address;
}
```

---

### 📊 XML Autowire vs @Autowired

| Point | XML `autowire` | `@Autowired` |
|---|---|---|
| Style | Old (Spring Framework) | Modern (Spring Boot) |
| Config file needed | Yes (beans.xml) | No |
| Default mode | byName / byType | byType |
| Ambiguity fix | Only one bean allowed | Use `@Qualifier("beanId")` |

---

### 🔑 Interview One-Liners

> **byName** → field name must match bean id  
> **byType** → field type must match bean class; fails if duplicates exist  
> **@Autowired** → Spring Boot way; works byType; use `@Qualifier` to resolve ambiguity  
> **@Autowired on constructor** → recommended approach (immutable, testable)
